{{Infobox building |name = 277 Park Avenue |image = 277parkave.jpg |image_size = 225px |caption = 277 Park Avenue |location = 277 Park Avenue, [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]] |coordinates = {{coord|40.755515|-73.975153|display=inline}} |status = Complete |start_date = 1962 |completion_date = 1964 |opening = July 13, 1964 |building_type = Office |antenna_spire = |roof = {{convert|687|ft|m|abbr=on}} |top_floor = |floor_count = 50 |elevator_count = |cost = |floor_area = {{convert|1,767,499|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|title=277 Park Avenue|url=http://www.skyscrapercenter.com/building/277-park-avenue/1481|website=Skyscraper Center|publisher=CTBUH|accessdate=14 September 2017}}</ref> |architect = [[Emery Roth|Emery Roth & Sons]] |structural_engineer= |main_contractor = |developer = Stanley Stahl |owner = Stahl Organization |management = Stahl Organization |references = }}
'''277 Park Avenue''' is an office building in the [[Midtown Manhattan]] neighborhood of [[New York City]]. It stands on the east side of [[Park Avenue]] between East 47th and 48th Streets; it is {{Convert|687|ft|m|0}} tall, with 50 floors.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aviewoncities.com/buildings/nyc/277parkavenue.htm |title=277 Park Avenue |work=aviewoncities.com |accessdate=2010-03-13}}</ref>
The building currently houses parts of [[JPMorgan Chase|JPMorgan Chase's]] Investment Bank, Commercial Bank, and other corporate functions. JP Morgan's takeover of [[Bear Stearns]] in 2008 resulted in most investment banking employees moving to [[383 Madison Avenue]] to reduce the leased real estate footprint in Midtown. 277 Park Avenue remains under the ownership of the family-owned Stahl Organization, the building's original developer.<ref>{{cite news |title=Stanley Stahl, a Bank Owner And Real Estate Investor, 75 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/08/06/nyregion/stanley-stahl-a-bank-owner-and-real-estate-investor-75.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=August 6, 1999 |accessdate=2014-07-17}}</ref>
Previous tenants have included [[Penthouse Magazine]], [[Schlumberger]], [[Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Chase Says It Has Deal for Park Avenue Spot |first=Charles V. |last=Bagli |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/12/02/nyregion/chase-says-it-has-deal-for-park-avenue-spot.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=December 2, 2000 |accessdate=2010-03-13}}</ref> and [[Chemical Bank]] (Predecessor to today's JPMorgan Chase). The office building opened on July 13, 1964.<ref>{{cite news |title=Chemical Bank Opens Doors of Tower on Park Avenue |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/07/13/archives/chemical-bank-opens-doors-of-tower-on-park-avenue.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=July 13, 1964 |accessdate=2010-03-13}}</ref>
An apartment building designed by [[McKim, Mead, and White]] previously occupied the site.<ref>{{cite news |title=A Vanished Circular Driveway, an Old Brochure |first=Christopher |last=Gray |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/03/17/realestate/streetscapes-readers-questions-a-vanished-circular-driveway-an-old-brochure.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=March 17, 1991 |accessdate=2010-03-13}}</ref> One tenant of that building was the presidential campaign of [[John F. Kennedy]].<ref>[http://untappedcities.com/2013/11/05/daily-what-john-f-kennedy-apartment-campaign-offices-277-park-avenue/ John F Kennedy campaign] The Daily What</ref>
==Tenants== *[[Academy Securities]]<ref>[http://www.academysecurities.com/]</ref> *[[Australia and New Zealand Banking Group]]<ref>[http://www.anz.com/unitedstates/en/about-us/our-company/anz-usa/ ANZ in the USA]</ref> *[[Bregal Investments]]<ref>[http://www.bregal.com/contact]</ref> *[[Bregal Partners]]<ref>[https://bregalpartners.com/home/contact/]</ref> *[[Bregal Sagemount]]<ref>[https://sagemount.com/contact]</ref> *[[Cassidy Turley]] *[[Cozen O’Connor]]<ref>[http://observer.com/2009/10/leases-pending-for-part-of-midtowns-biggest-sublease-space/ Leases Pending for Part of Midtown’s Biggest Sublease Space]</ref> *[[The Hartford]]<ref>[http://www.rew-online.com/2011/04/01/the-hartford-takes-two-floors-at-277-park-avenue/ The Hartford takes two floors at 277 Park Avenue]</ref> *[[JPMorgan Chase]] *[[Sumitomo Mitsui Banking Corporation]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smbcgroup.com/americas/us/ny|title=New York|website=www.smbcgroup.com|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref> *[[ContiGroup Companies|Continental Grain Company]] *[[MHP Real Estate Services]] *[[Agricultural Bank of China]]<ref>[http://www.us.abchina.com/en/contact_us/ Agricultural Bank of China New York Branch]</ref> *[[Bank of India, US Operations]]<ref>[http://www.boiusa.com/]</ref> *[[Raymond James & Associates]]<ref>[http://www.raymondjames.com/]</ref>
