'''Björn Georg Wilhelm Westerlund''', titled ''[[Vuorineuvos]]'' (27 January 1912 in [[Hanover]], [[German Empire|Germany]] &ndash; 11 March 2009 in [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]]), was a Finnish businessman and a short-time minister in the [[government of Finland]]. He was the former and first President and CEO of [[Nokia|Nokia Corporation]] that was formed in a 1967 merger between the three Finnish companies Nokia Company, [[Nokian Footwear|Finnish Rubber Works]] and [[Kaapelitehdas|Kaapelitehdas (Cable Company)]]. He was the CEO until his retirement in 1977. He remained Chairman of the Board until 1979.

He was also the [[Minister of Trade and Industry (Finland)|Minister of Trade and Industry]] for a short while (19 June to 14 July 1961)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://valtioneuvosto.fi/tietoa/historiaa/hallitukset-ja-ministerit/raportti/-/r/v9l/6|title=Finnish Government - Ministers of Trade and Industry|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Valtioneuvosto.fi|archive-url=|archive-date=|deadurl=no|accessdate=30 March 2018}}</ref> in [[V. J. Sukselainen]]'s [[Vieno Johannes Sukselainen's second cabinet|second government]], as a representative of [[Swedish People's Party (Finland)|Swedish People's Party]].

